  "prompt": "Can someone build a product based on an idea he pitched to his ex company, if the company never cared to productize it?",
  "response": "Generally speaking, whether someone can build a product based on an idea they pitched to their ex-company that was never productized depends on several factors related to intellectual property, employment contracts, and confidentiality agreements. Here are key considerations:\n\n1. **Employment Contract Terms:** Review the terms of your employment contract. Many companies have clauses regarding intellectual property developed during employment. If your contract stipulates that ideas conceived during employment belong to the company, you might face legal issues.\n\n2. **Confidentiality Agreements:** If you signed a non-disclosure agreement (NDA) or confidentiality agreement, you need to ensure that you're not using proprietary information or trade secrets when developing your own product.\n\n3. **Ownership of Ideas:** If the idea was developed or significantly improved using company resources, it might be considered the company's intellectual property. If you developed the idea independently or outside of your employment, you might have more freedom.\n\n4. **Legal Advice:** Consult with a legal professional specializing in intellectual property and employment law. They can provide advice specific to your situation and jurisdiction.\n\n5. **Non-Compete Clauses:** If your employment contract included a non-compete clause, you need to ensure that developing the product does not violate this agreement.\n\nIn summary, while it might be possible, you need to carefully review your previous employment agreements and possibly seek legal counsel to ensure you are not violating any terms or laws.",
